x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">It doesn=E2=80=99t =
sound like that much for a <b>Lucian Freud</b> portrait, especially one of =
a naked woman. But only a dozen paintings by Freud have sold for more than =
=C2=A310 million. Of course, one of those dozen was <i>Benefits Supervisor =
Resting</i>, which sold for <i>$56 million</i> in 2015, a peak in the marke=
t, to <b>Roman Abramovich</b>. <br/><br/>Oligarchs don=E2=80=99t drive the =
market much these days. Or, at least, we don=E2=80=99t hear about their pur=
chases nearly as much as we did a decade ago, before the first invasion of =
Ukraine. Two years ago, a new record was set for Freud at $86 million for a=
 seminal early work, <i>Large Interior, W11 (after Watteau),</i> painted in=
 1981. Now, Christie=E2=80=99s is offering <i>Ria, Naked Portrait</i>, a la=
te Freud painting from 2006-07, which the auction house=E2=80=99s <b>Kathar=
ine Arnold</b> likens to one of the artist=E2=80=99s
favorite works, <b>Vel=C3=A1zquez</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Rokeby Venus </i>(1647-5=
1). Arnold notes that <i>Ria, Naked Portrait</i> =E2=80=9Cwould later hang =
alone in the final room of the National Portrait Gallery=E2=80=99s landmark=
 retrospective in 2012=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94still one of the most popular ticke=
ted shows in the gallery=E2=80=99s history.<br/><br/><i>And now, on to the =
main event=E2=80=A6</i><br/></td>
