arent holding company=E2=80=94Sotheby=E2=80=99s had an average employee hea=
dcount of 2,242 in 2023, slightly more than a quarter of whom were located =
in the U.K. (although that number may include part-time workers). Since the=
n, Sotheby=E2=80=99s has reduced staffing in London by about 50 people, or =
around 12 percent.<br/><br/>The other unsolved mystery is when Sotheby=E2=
=80=99s will close on the Breuer building, which is the centerpiece of the =
firm=E2=80=99s new-look strategy. When the real estate deal was announced, =
the target date for Sotheby=E2=80=99s to take the keys was this month. Soth=
eby=E2=80=99s says it was always planning to close some time this fall. Amo=
ng the gossipy world of ex-Sotheby=E2=80=99s employees, there have been con=
stant rumors all year that Sotheby=E2=80=99s would not have the money to cl=
ose. Is that transaction <i>possibly </i>also awaiting the Emiratis=E2=80=
=99
wire?<br/><br/>When Sotheby=E2=80=99s moves out of its York Avenue headquar=
ters, its New York footprint will be split between the Breuer building, on =
Madison Avenue, and a new back office and logistics facility in Long Island=
 City. The move to the Breuer building was always assumed to be an opportun=
ity to unlock the full value of the York Avenue building, designed by forme=
r Sotheby=E2=80=99s owner and luxury mall pioneer <b>Alfred Taubman</b>, wh=
